es specifically on their views of the self and its realization, their understandings of women and the relation between the sexes, and their speculative conceptions of politics. While there are many similarities in their positive visions, Franco argues that it is the differences between them from which we have most to learn.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPhilosophical anthropology. 0aPhilosophy, Modern. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aSelf. 0aWoman (Philosophy) 0aWoman (Philosophy). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  anietzsche, rousseau, philosophy, modern life, society, modernity, civic virtue, division, community, hypocrisy, equality, democracy, genius, individuality, freedom, success, ambition, women, gender, self, growth, independence, politics, nonfiction, family, relationships, liberalism, enlightenment, sexual difference, nature, humanity, authenticity, humanism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021 Englishz978311075417908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021z9783110753943oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831107391900 cprintz978022680030140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226800448423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226800448/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075417-9  EBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021 Englishb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-PLWb2021